The course combines theory and practice, providing an overview of the theory of translation and the practical principles of translators' and interpreters' work. Furthermore, it allows the students to develop their practical language skills and sense of style in their mother tongue and in one of the Scandinavian languages (Norwegian/Swedish/Danish). The theoretical topics covered are: the central concepts in translation theory; translation as a process; different models of translation; the translation product and equivalence. The working principles of written translation, simultaneous and consecutive interpretation are addressed separately. For the practical part, different types of Norwegian/Swedish/Danish texts will be translated and a variety of exercises in oral translation will be carried out.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to provide students with a basic knowledge of translation theory's main concepts and terminology; introduce the central working principles of written translation, consecutive and simultaneous interpretation; train practical translation skills of Norwegian/Swedish/Danish into Estonian and develop proficiency levels required for the translation work.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course, the student: - knows the theoretical fundaments of translation theory and has an introductory overview of contemporary schools and trends; - knows the main working principles of written translation, consecutive and simultaneous interpretation and understands the links and differences between different forms of translation; - knows cultural differences and takes them into account in translation and interpretation; - understands the quality requirements for the profession of translators and interpreters, as well as general ethical and moral principles; - uses digital resources necessary for a translator; - translates texts of medium difficulty and different functionalities from Norwegian/Swedish/Danish to Estonian."
